Definition 4.2. With notation as above we denote by $A_{\otimes}(\operatorname{Inj}R)$ the quotient $\ker(H)/\mathsf{K}_{\mathrm{pac}}(\operatorname{Flat}R)$, where $\ker(H)=\{F\in\mathsf{K}(\operatorname{Flat}R)\;|\;H(\Sigma^{i}F)=0\;\forall i% \in\mathbb{Z}\}.$
Definition 1.6. A triangulated subcategory $\mathsf{I}$ of $\mathsf{K}$ is thick if it is closed under taking direct summands, i.e. if $k\oplus k^{\prime}\in\mathsf{I}$ then both $k$ and $k^{\prime}$ lie in $\mathsf{I}$. To be very explicit: a full subcategory $\mathsf{I}$ of $\mathsf{K}$ is thick if it is closed under suspensions, cones, and direct summands. A thick subcategory $\mathsf{I}$ of $\mathsf{K}$ is a (thick) tensor-ideal if given any $k\in\mathsf{K}$ and $l\in\mathsf{I}$ the tensor product $k\otimes l$ lies in $\mathsf{I}$. Put another way we require the functor $\mathsf{K}\times\mathsf{I}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\otimes}}{{\longrightarrow}}% \mathsf{K}$ to factor through $\mathsf{I}$. Finally, a proper thick tensor-ideal $\mathsf{P}$ of $\mathsf{K}$ is prime if given $k,l\in\mathsf{K}$ such that $k\otimes l\in\mathsf{P}$ then at least one of $k$ or $l$ lies in $\mathsf{P}$. We will often just call prime tensor-ideals in $\mathsf{K}$ prime ideals.
Definition 3.14. We will say the tensor triangulated category $\mathsf{T}$ has a model if it occurs as the homotopy category of a monoidal model category.
Definition 2.8. Let $\mathsf{L}$ be a triangulated subcategory of $\mathsf{T}$. The subcategory $\mathsf{L}$ is localising if it is closed under arbitrary coproducts in $\mathsf{T}$. Dually, it is colocalising if it is closed under arbitrary products in $\mathsf{T}$. Put another way, a full subcategory of $\mathsf{T}$ is localising if it is closed under suspensions, cones, and coproducts and colocalising if it is closed under suspensions, cones, and products. Let $\mathsf{I}$ be a localising subcategory of $\mathsf{T}$. We call $\mathsf{I}$ a localising tensor-ideal if for any $X\in\mathsf{T}$ and $Y\in\mathsf{I}$ the object $X\otimes Y$ lies in $\mathsf{I}$. Given a family of objects $S\subseteq\mathsf{T}$ we denote by $\operatorname{loc}(S)$ (resp. $\operatorname{loc}^{\otimes}(S)$) the smallest localising subcategory (resp. localising tensor-ideal) of $\mathsf{T}$ containing $S$ and by $\operatorname{Loc}(\mathsf{T})$ (resp. $\operatorname{Loc}^{\otimes}(\mathsf{T})$) the collection of all localising subcategories (resp. localising tensor-ideals) of $\mathsf{T}$.
Definition 1.17. The Zariski topology on $\operatorname{Spc}\mathsf{K}$ is the topology defined by the basis of closed subsets $\{\operatorname{supp}k\;|\;k\in\mathsf{K}\}$ The closed subsets of $\operatorname{Spc}\mathsf{K}$ are of the form $\displaystyle Z(S)$ $\displaystyle=\{\mathsf{P}\in\operatorname{Spc}\mathsf{K}\;|\;S\cap\mathsf{P}=\varnothing\}$ $\displaystyle=\bigcap_{k\in S}\operatorname{supp}(k)$ where $S\subseteq\mathsf{K}$ is an arbitrary family of objects.
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathsf{L}\subseteq\mathsf{K}$ be a localising (thick) subcategory of $\mathsf{K}$. We say $\mathsf{L}$ is a localising (thick) $\mathsf{T}$-submodule of $\mathsf{K}$ if the functor $\mathsf{T}\times\mathsf{L}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle*}}{{\longrightarrow}}\mathsf% {K}$ factors via $\mathsf{L}$, i.e. $\mathsf{L}$ is closed under the action of $\mathsf{T}$. In the case that $\mathsf{K}=\mathsf{T}$ acts on itself by $\otimes$ this recovers the notion of a localising (thick) tensor-ideal of $\mathsf{T}$. We mean the obvious things by a smashing or compactly generated (by compact objects in the ambient category) submodule.
Definition 4.8. The singular locus of $R$ is the set $\operatorname{Sing}(R)=\{\mathfrak{p}\in\operatorname{Spec}R\;|\;R_{\mathfrak{% p}}\;\text{is not regular}\},$ i.e. the collection of those prime ideals $\mathfrak{p}$ such that $R_{\mathfrak{p}}$ has infinite global dimension. Recall that this is equivalent to the residue field $k(\mathfrak{p})$ having infinite projective dimension over $R_{\mathfrak{p}}$.
Definition 1.27. Let $X$ be a spectral space and let $W\subseteq X$ be a subset of $X$. We say $W$ is specialisation closed if for any $w\in W$ and $w^{\prime}\in\overline{\{w\}}$ we have $w^{\prime}\in W$. That is, $W$ is specialisation closed if it is the union of the closures of its elements. Given $w,w^{\prime}$ as above we call $w^{\prime}$ a specialisation of $w$. Dually, we say $W$ is generisation closed if given any $w^{\prime}\in W$ and a $w\in X$ such that $w^{\prime}\in\overline{\{w\}}$ then we have $w\in W$. In this situation we call $w$ a generisation of $w^{\prime}$. A Thomason subset of $X$ is a subset of the form $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}V_{\lambda}$ where each $V_{\lambda}$ is a closed subset of $X$ with quasi-compact complement. Note that any Thomason subset is specialisation closed. We denote by $\operatorname{Thom}(X)$ the collection of Thomason subsets of $X$. It is a poset with respect to inclusion and in fact also carries the structure of a complete lattice where the join is given by taking unions.
Definition 2.21. For every $x\in\operatorname{Spc}\mathsf{T}^{c}$ we define subsets of the spectrum $\mathcal{V}(x)=\overline{\{x\}}$ and $\mathcal{Z}(x)=\{y\in\operatorname{Spc}\mathsf{T}^{c}\;|\;x\notin\mathcal{V}(y% )\}.$ Both of these subsets are specialization closed and hence Thomason as we have assumed $\operatorname{Spc}\mathsf{T}^{c}$ is noetherian. We note that $\mathcal{V}(x)\setminus(\mathcal{Z}(x)\cap\mathcal{V}(x))=\{x\}$ i.e. these two Thomason subsets let us pick out the point $x$.
Definition 4.3. A lifting of a crossed module $(A,B,\alpha)$ is called universal if it lifts to every lifting of $(A,B,\alpha)$.
Definition 4.1. Let $(A,B,\alpha)$ be a crossed module and $\omega\colon X\rightarrow B$ a morphism of groups. Then a crossed module $(A,X,\varphi)$ in which the action of $X$ on $A$ is defined via $\omega$, is a called a lifting of $\alpha$ over $\omega$ and denoted by $(\varphi,X,\omega)$ if the following diagram is commutative $\xymatrix{&X\ar[d]^{\omega}\\ A\ar[r]_{-}\alpha\ar@{-->}[ur]^{\varphi}&B}$
Definition 4.2. Let $(A,B,\alpha)$ be a crossed module. A lifting $(\varphi,X,\omega)$ of $(A,B,\alpha)$ is called transitive if both crossed modules $(A,B,\alpha)$ and $(A,X,\varphi)$ are transitive.
Definition 3.1. Let $(A,B,\alpha)$ be a crossed module. Then $(A,B,\alpha)$ is called transitive (resp. simply transitive, 1-transitive and totally intransitive) if $\alpha$ is surjective (resp. injective, bijective; and zero morphism such that $A$ is abelian).
Definition 3. An occurrence of the variable $x$ is strongly positive in a formula-term $\phi$ if there is no subformula $\psi$ of $\phi$ of the form $\psi_{0}\rightarrow\psi_{1}$ such that $x$ is located in $\psi_{0}$. A formula-term $\phi$ is strongly positive in the variable $x$ if every occurrence of $x$ is strongly positive in $\phi$. An occurrence of a variable $x$ is weakly negative in a formula-term $\phi$ if it is not strongly positive. A formula-term $\phi$ is weakly negative in the variable $x$ if every occurrence of $x$ is weakly negative in $\phi$.
Definition 1. A Heyting algebra $H$ is a bounded lattice (with least element $\bot$ and greatest element $\top$) equipped with a binary operation $\rightarrow$ such that the following equations hold in $H$: $\displaystyle x\land(x\rightarrow y)$ $\displaystyle=x\land y\,,$ $\displaystyle x\land(y\rightarrow x)$ $\displaystyle=x\,,$ $\displaystyle x\rightarrow x$ $\displaystyle=\top\,,$ $\displaystyle x\rightarrow(y\land z)$ $\displaystyle=(x\rightarrow y)\land(x\rightarrow z)\,.$
Definition 2. Let $H$ be a Heyting algebra. We say that a function $f:H\xrightarrow{\quad}H$ is monotone polynomial if there exist a formula $\phi$ of the \Ipc, a variable $x$ positive in $\phi$, and a valuation $\vec{v}:\mathbb{X}_{\phi}\setminus\{\,x\,\}\xrightarrow{\quad}H$ such that, for each $h\in H$, we have $f(h)=\llbracket\phi\rrbracket_{\vec{v},h/x}$.
Definition 4. The set of formula-terms that are disjunctive in the variable $x$ is generated by the following grammar: $\displaystyle\phi$ $\displaystyle\;\;\Rightarrow\;\;x\mid\beta\vee\phi\mid\phi\vee\beta\mid\alpha% \rightarrow\phi\mid\phi\vee\phi\,,$ where $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are formulas with no occurrence of the variable $x$. A formula-term $\phi$ is in normal form (w.r.t. $x$) if it is a conjunction of formula-terms $\phi_{i}$, $i\in I$, so that each $\phi_{i}$ either does not contain the variable $x$, or it is disjunctive in $x$.
Definition 3.12. A pair of subcategories $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ in a triangulated category $\mathcal{T}$ is called a torsion pair if (1) $\mathcal{U}$ and $\mathcal{V}$ are closed under summands; (2) $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})=0$; (3) For any object $X$ in $\mathcal{T}$ there are objects $U$ in $\mathcal{U}$, $V$ in $\mathcal{V}$ and a triangle $U\longrightarrow X\longrightarrow V\longrightarrow U[1].$ If $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ is a torsion pair in $\mathcal{T}$, then we say that $\mathcal{U}$ is a torsion class and $\mathcal{V}$ is a torsionfree class.
Definition 2.1. A subcategory $\mathcal{X}$ of an additive category $\mathcal{A}$ is said to be • precovering if for every object $A$ in $\mathcal{A}$ there is $X$ in $\mathcal{X}$ and a morphism $f\colon X\longrightarrow A$ such that $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(X^{\prime},f)$ is surjective for all $X^{\prime}$ in $\mathcal{X}$. The map $f$ is then called a $\mathcal{X}$-precover of $A$. • preenveloping if for every object $A$ in $\mathcal{A}$ there is $X$ in $\mathcal{X}$ and a morphism $f\colon A\longrightarrow X$ such that $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(f,X^{\prime})$ is surjective for all $X^{\prime}$ in $\mathcal{X}$. The map $f$ is then called a $\mathcal{X}$-preenvelope of $A$. • covering if every object $A$ in $\mathcal{A}$ admits a right minimal $\mathcal{X}$-precover (i.e. a $\mathcal{X}$-precover $f\colon X\longrightarrow~{}A$ such that any endomorphism $g$ of $X$ with the property that $fg=f$ must be an automorphism). • enveloping if every object $A$ in $\mathcal{A}$ admits a left minimal $\mathcal{X}$-preenvelope (i.e. a $\mathcal{X}$-preenvelope $f\colon A\longrightarrow X$ such that any endomorphism $g$ of $X$ with the property that $gf=f$ must be an automorphism). • coreflective if the inclusion functor of $\mathcal{X}$ into $\mathcal{A}$ admits a right adjoint. • reflective if the inclusion functor of $\mathcal{X}$ into $\mathcal{A}$ admits a left adjoint. • bireflective if the inclusion functor of $\mathcal{X}$ into $\mathcal{A}$ admits both a left and a right adjoint.
Definition 4.6. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a compactly generated triangulated category. An additive (covariant) functor $F\colon\mathcal{T}\longrightarrow\mathsf{Mod}(\mathbb{Z})$ is said to be coherent if there is an exact sequence $\xymatrix{\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(Y,-)\ar[rr]^{\operatorname{Hom}_{% \mathcal{T}}(f,-)}&&\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(X,-)\ar[rr]&&F\ar[rr]&&0}$ with $f\colon X\longrightarrow Y$ a map in $\mathcal{T}^{c}$. A subcategory $\mathcal{X}$ of $\mathcal{T}$ is said to be definable if there is a set of coherent functors $(F_{i})_{i\in I}$ such that $F_{i}(X)=0$ for all $i$ in $I$ if and only if $X$ lies in $\mathcal{X}$.
Definition 2.10. If $\mathcal{T}$ is a triangulated category with coproducts, then • an object $X$ in $\mathcal{T}$ is compact if $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(X,-)$ commutes with direct sums; • $\mathcal{T}$ is said to be compactly generated if the subcategory of compact objects, denoted by $\mathcal{T}^{c}$, is skeletally small and generates $\mathcal{T}$ (i.e. if $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(C,X)=0$ for all $C$ compact, then $X\cong 0$).
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a compactly generated algebraic triangulated category. We will say that a subcategory $\mathcal{X}$ is closed under homotopy colimits if there exists a small dg category $\mathcal{A}$ and an equivalence $F\colon\mathcal{T}\rightarrow\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{A})$ such that $F(\mathcal{X})$ is closed under homotopy colimits in $\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{A})$.
Definition 5.8. If $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ is a torsion pair, then we say that it is • a t-structure if $\mathcal{U}$ is suspended (or, equivalently, if $\mathcal{V}$ is cosuspended); • a co-t-structure if $\mathcal{U}$ is cosuspended (or, equivalently, if $\mathcal{V}$ is suspended); • left nondegenerate if $\bigcap_{i\in\mathbb{Z}}\mathcal{U}[i]=0$; • right nondegenerate if $\bigcap_{i\in\mathbb{Z}}\mathcal{V}[i]=0$.
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a cocomplete additive category (i.e. an additive category with all colimits). An object $A$ in $\mathcal{A}$ is finitely presented if $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(A,-)$ commutes with directed colimits. The category $\mathcal{A}$ is said to be locally finitely presented if there is a set $\mathcal{S}$ of finitely presented objects such that every object of $\mathcal{A}$ is a directed colimit of objects in $\mathcal{S}$.
Definition 6.2. A triangulated subcategory $\mathcal{S}$ of a triangulated category $\mathcal{T}$ with products and coproducts is said to be smashing if $\mathcal{S}$ is coreflective and $\mathcal{S}^{\perp}$ is closed under coproducts. Dually, we say that a triangulated subcategory $\mathcal{C}$ is cosmashing if it is reflective and ${}^{\perp}\mathcal{C}$ is closed under products.
Definition 3.10. A triangulated category is called algebraic if it is equivalent to the stable category of a Frobenius exact category.
Definition 6.1. A diagram of triangulated categories and triangle functors of the form $\xymatrix@C=0.5cm{\mathcal{B}\ar[rrr]^{i_{*}}&&&\mathcal{T}\ar[rrr]^{j^{*}}\ar% @/_{1}.5pc/[lll]_{i^{*}}\ar@/^{1}.5pc/[lll]_{i^{!}}&&&\mathcal{Y}\ar@/_{1}.5pc% /[lll]_{j_{!}}\ar@/^{1}.5pc/[lll]_{j_{*}}}$ is said to be a recollement of $\mathcal{T}$ if (1) $(i^{*},i_{*},i^{!})$ and $(j_{!},j^{*},j_{*})$ are adjoint triples; (2) $i_{*}$, $j_{!}$ and $j_{*}$ are fully faithful; and (3) $\mbox{\rm{Im\,}}i_{*}=\mbox{\rm{Ker}}\,j^{*}$. Two recollements given by triples $(i^{*},i_{*},i^{!})$, $(j_{!},j^{*},j_{*})$ and $(i^{\prime*},i_{*}^{\prime},i^{\prime!})$, $(j_{!}^{\prime},j^{\prime*},j_{*}^{\prime})$ respectively are equivalent if $\mbox{\rm{Im\,}}i_{*}=\mbox{\rm{Im\,}}i_{*}^{\prime}$, $\mbox{\rm{Im\,}}j_{!}=\mbox{\rm{Im\,}}j_{!}^{\prime}$ and $\mbox{\rm{Im\,}}j_{*}=\mbox{\rm{Im\,}}j_{*}^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.11. A triangle in a compactly generated triangulated category $\mathcal{T}$ $\Delta\colon\xymatrix{L\ar[r]^{f}&M\ar[r]^{g}&N\ar[r]&L[1]}$ is said to be a pure triangle if $\mathbf{y}(\Delta)$ is a short exact sequence in $\mathsf{Mod}(\mathcal{T}^{c})$. In that case we say that $f$ is a pure monomorphism, $g$ is a pure epimorphism, $L$ is a pure subobject of $M$ and $N$ is a pure quotient of $M$. Moreover, an object $L$ is pure-injective if every pure triangle of the form $\Delta$ splits. An object $N$ is pure-projective if every pure triangle of the form $\Delta$ splits.
Definition 2.3. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a cocomplete additive category. A morphism $f\colon X\longrightarrow Y$ is said to be a pure monomorphism (respectively, a pure epimorphism) in $\mathcal{A}$ if there is a directed system of split monomorphisms (respectively, split epimorphisms) $(f_{i}\colon X_{i}\longrightarrow Y_{i})_{i\in I}$ such that $f=\varinjlim_{I}f_{i}$. An object $X$ is said to be a pure subobject (respectively, a pure quotient) of $Y$ if there is a pure monomorphism $X\longrightarrow Y$ (respectively, a pure epimorphism $X\longrightarrow Y$).
Definition 2.8. A subcategory $\mathcal{U}$ of $\mathcal{T}$ is suspended (respectively, cosuspended) if it is closed under summands and extensions, and $\mathcal{U}[1]$ is contained in $\mathcal{U}$ (respectively, $\mathcal{U}[-1]$ is contained in $\mathcal{U}$). Moreover, a subcategory $\mathcal{U}$ is triangulated if it is both suspended and cosuspended.
Definition 3.6. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a small dg category and $\mathcal{X}$ a subcategory of $\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{A})$. (1) The preimage of $\mathcal{X}$ in $\mathcal{C}(\mathcal{A})$ is the subcategory $\pi^{-1}(\mathcal{X}):=\{X\in\mathcal{C}(\mathcal{A})\mid\pi(X)\in\mathcal{X}\}.$ (2) The subcategory $\mathcal{X}$ is closed under directed homotopy colimits if for every directed small category $S$ and every object $X=(X_{s})_{s\in S}$ in $\mathcal{C}(\mathcal{A})^{S}$ such that $\pi(X_{s})$ is in $\mathcal{X}$ for every $s$ in $S$, we have that $\mathbb{L}\varinjlim_{S}\pi_{S}X$ is in $\mathcal{X}$.
Definition 5.6. If a subcategory $\mathcal{Z}$ of $\mathcal{T}$ is simultaneously a torsion and a torsionfree class, then we call $\mathcal{Z}$ a TTF class and $({}^{\perp}\mathcal{Z},\mathcal{Z},\mathcal{Z}^{\perp})$ a TTF triple. Moreover, we say that the torsion pairs $({}^{\perp}\mathcal{Z},\mathcal{Z})$ and $(\mathcal{Z},\mathcal{Z}^{\perp})$ are adjacent.
Definition 3.13. Let $\mathcal{F}$ be an exact category. We say that a pair of subcategories $(\mathcal{M},\mathcal{N})$ of $\mathcal{F}$ is a complete cotorsion pair if the following statements hold. • $\mathcal{N}=\mbox{\rm{Ker}}\,\operatorname{Ext}^{1}_{\mathcal{F}}(\mathcal{M},-)$ and $\mathcal{M}=\mbox{\rm{Ker}}\,\operatorname{Ext}^{1}_{\mathcal{F}}(-,\mathcal{N})$. • $\mathcal{M}$ is special precovering, i.e. for every object $X$ in $\mathcal{F}$ there are objects $M_{1}$ in $\mathcal{M}$, $N_{1}$ in $\mathcal{N}$ and a conflation $\xymatrix{0\ar[r]&N_{1}\ar[r]&M_{1}\ar[r]^{f}&X\ar[r]&0.}$ • $\mathcal{N}$ is special preenveloping, i.e. for every object $X$ in $\mathcal{F}$ there are objects $N_{2}$ in $\mathcal{N}$, $M_{2}$ in $\mathcal{M}$ and a conflation $\xymatrix{0\ar[r]&X\ar[r]^{g}&N_{2}\ar[r]&M_{2}\ar[r]&0.}$
Definition 4.2. (cf. [3]) Let $U:\mathcal{E}\rightarrow\mathbf{Set}$ be topological, $X\in Ob(\mathcal{E})$ with $U(X)=Y$ and $p\in Y$. (i) $\{p\}$ is closed iff the initial lift of the $U$-source $\{A^{\infty}_{p}:\vee^{\infty}_{p}Y\rightarrow Y^{\infty}$ and $\nabla^{\infty}_{p}:\vee^{\infty}_{p}Y\rightarrow UD(Y^{\infty})=Y^{\infty}\}$ is discrete, where $D$ is the discrete functor. (ii) $X$ is $D$-connected iff any morphism from $X$ to any discrete object is constant.
Definition 3.3. A map $\nabla_{p}:X\vee_{p}X\rightarrow X$ is called folding map at $p$ if $\nabla_{p}(x_{i})=x$ for $i=1,2$.
Definition 2.7. (cf. [20]) Let $\mathcal{B}(x)\subset L^{X}$, for all $x\in X$. Then, $(\mathcal{B}(x))_{x\in X}$ is called $L$-approach system basis if for all $x\in X$, (i) $\mathcal{B}(x)$ is a filter basis in $L^{X}$. (ii) $\varphi(x)=\top$ whenever $\varphi\in\mathcal{B}(x)$. (iii) For all $\varphi\in\mathcal{B}(x)$, $\alpha\lhd\top$, $\bot\prec\omega$ there exists a family $(\varphi_{z})_{z\in X}\in\prod_{z\in X}\mathcal{B}(z)$ such that $\varphi_{x}(z)*\varphi_{z}(y)*\alpha\leq\varphi(y)\vee\omega$, $\forall y,z\in X$.
Definition 3.1. (cf. [2]) A map $A_{p}:X\vee_{p}X\rightarrow X^{2}$ is called principal $p$-axis map if $\begin{array}[]{rlll}A_{p}(x_{i})=\begin{cases}(x,p),&\text{ $i=1$}\\ (p,x),&\text{$i=2$}\end{cases}&&&\end{array}$
Definition 2.5. (cf. [20]) Let $\mathcal{A}\subseteq L^{X}$ and $\varphi\in L^{X}$. (i) $\varphi$ is supported by $\mathcal{A}$ if for all $\alpha\lhd\top$, $\bot\prec\omega$ there exists $\varphi_{\alpha}^{\omega}\in\mathcal{A}$ such that $\varphi_{\alpha}^{\omega}*\alpha\leq\varphi\vee\omega$. (ii) $\mathcal{A}$ is saturated if $\varphi\in\mathcal{A}$ whenever $\varphi$ is supported by $\mathcal{A}$. (iii) For $\mathcal{B}\subseteq L^{X}$, $\tilde{\mathcal{B}}=\{\varphi\in L^{X}:\varphi$ is supported by $\mathcal{B}\}$ is called saturation of $\mathcal{B}$.
Definition 4.1. (cf. [3]) (i) A map $A^{\infty}_{p}:\vee^{\infty}_{p}X\rightarrow X^{\infty}$ is called infinite principle axis map at $p$ if $A^{\infty}_{p}(x_{i})=(p,p,....,p,x,p,...)$. (ii) A map $\nabla^{\infty}_{p}:\vee^{\infty}_{p}X\rightarrow X^{\infty}$ is called infinite folding map $p$ if $\nabla^{\infty}_{p}(x_{i})=x$ for all $i\in I$.
Definition 2.1. (cf. [19]) An L-metric on a set $X$ is a map $d:X\times X\rightarrow(L,\leq,*)$ satisfies for all $x\in X$, $d(x,x)=\top$, and for all $x,y,z\in X$, $d(x,y)*d(y,z)\leq d(x,z)$.
Definition 2.4. (cf. [19]) A map $\delta:X\times P(X)\rightarrow(L,\leq,*)$ is called $L$-approach if $\delta$ satisfies the followings: (i) $\forall x\in X$: $\delta(x,\{x\})=\top$. (ii) $\forall x\in X$ and $\emptyset$, the empty set: $\delta(x,\emptyset)=\bot$. (iii) $\forall x\in X$ and $\forall A,B\subseteq X$: $\delta(x,A\cup B)=\delta(x,A)\vee\delta(x,B)$. (iv) $\forall x\in X$, $\forall A\subseteq X$ and $\forall\alpha\in L$: $\delta(x,A)\geq\delta(x,\overline{A}^{\alpha})*\alpha$, where $\overline{A}^{\alpha}=\{x\in X:\delta(x,A)\geq\alpha\}$. The pair $(X,\delta)$ is called $L$-Approach distance space.
Definition 2.2. (cf. [19]) Let $\mathcal{H}\subseteq\textbf{L-MET(X)}$ and $d\in\textbf{L-MET(X)}$. (i) $d$ is called locally supported by $\mathcal{H}$ if for all $x\in X$, $\alpha\lhd\top$, $\bot\prec\omega$, there is $e\in\mathcal{H}$ such that $e(x,.)*\alpha\leq d(x,.)\vee\omega$. (ii) $\mathcal{H}$ is called locally directed if for all subsets $\mathcal{H}_{0}\subseteq\mathcal{H}$, $\bigwedge_{d\in\mathcal{H}_{0}}d$ is locally supported by $\mathcal{H}$. (iii) $\mathcal{H}$ is called locally saturated if for all $d\in\textbf{L-MET(X)}$, we have $d\in\mathcal{H}$ whenever $d$ is locally supported by $\mathcal{H}$. (iv) The set $\tilde{\mathcal{H}}=\{d\in\textbf{L-MET(X)}:d$ is locally supported by $\mathcal{H}\}$ is called local saturation of $\mathcal{H}$.
Definition 2.8. (cf. [20]) Let $(\mathcal{A}(x))_{x\in X}$ is called an $L$-approach system and $(\mathcal{B}(x))_{x\in X}$ be the collection of filter bases on $L^{X}$. Then, $(\mathcal{B}(x))_{x\in X}$ is called base for $L$-approach system if $\tilde{\mathcal{B}}(x)=\{\varphi\in L^{X}:\varphi$ is supported by $\mathcal{B}(x)\}=\mathcal{A}(x)$.
Definition 2.3. (cf. [19]) Let $X$ be a set. $\mathcal{G}\subseteq\textbf{L-MET(X)}$ is called an $L$-gauge if $\mathcal{G}$ satisfies the followings: (i) $\mathcal{G}\not=\emptyset$. (ii) $d\in\mathcal{G}$ and $d\leq e$ implies $e\in\mathcal{G}$. (iii) $d,e\in\mathcal{G}$ implies $d\wedge e\in\mathcal{G}$. (iv) $\mathcal{G}$ is locally saturated. The pair $(X,\mathcal{G})$ is called an $L$-gauge space.
Definition 3.2. A map $S_{p}:X\vee_{p}X\rightarrow X^{2}$ is called skewed $p$-axis map if $\begin{array}[]{rlll}S_{p}(x_{i})=\begin{cases}(x,x),&\text{ $i=1$}\\ (p,x),&\text{$i=2$}\end{cases}&&&\end{array}$
Definition 2.6. (cf. [20]) Let $\mathcal{A}(x)\subseteq L^{X}$, for all $x\in X$. Then, $\mathcal{A}=(\mathcal{A}(x))_{x\in X}$ is called an $L$-approach system if for all $x\in X$, (i) $\mathcal{A}(x)$ is a filter in $L^{X}$, i.e., $\varphi\in\mathcal{A}(x)$ and $\varphi\leq\varphi^{\prime}$ implies $\varphi^{\prime}\in\mathcal{A}(x)$, and $\varphi,\varphi^{\prime}\in\mathcal{A}(x)$ implies $\varphi\wedge\varphi^{\prime}\in\mathcal{A}(x)$. (ii) $\varphi(x)=\top$ whenever $\varphi\in\mathcal{A}(x)$. (iii) $\mathcal{A}(x)$ is saturated. (iv) For all $\varphi\in\mathcal{A}(x)$, $\alpha\lhd\top$, $\bot\prec\omega$ there exists a family $(\varphi_{z})_{z\in X}\in\prod_{z\in X}\mathcal{A}(z)$ such that $\varphi_{x}(z)*\varphi_{z}(y)*\alpha\leq\varphi(y)\vee\omega$, $\forall y,z\in X$. The pair $(X,\mathcal{A})$ is called an $L$-approach system space.
Definition 7 Let $A$ be a $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$ring and let $S\subseteq A$. The $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$ring of fractions of $A$ with respect to $S$ is a pair $(A\{S^{-1}\},\eta_{S}:A\to A\{S^{-1}\})$ where $A\{S^{-1}\}$ is a $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$ring and $\eta_{S}:A\to A\{S^{-1}\}$ is a $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$homomorphism such that: (i) $\eta_{S}[S]\subseteq(A\{S^{-1}\})^{\times}$; (ii) $\eta_{S}$ satisfies the following universal property: given any $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$homomorphism $g:A\to C$ such that $g[S]\subseteq C^{\times}$, there is a unique $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$homomorphism $\widetilde{g}:A\{S^{-1}\}\to C$ such that the following diagram commutes: $\xymatrixcolsep{5pc}\xymatrix{A\ar[r]^{\eta_{S}}\ar[dr]_{g}&A\{S^{-1}\}\ar[d]^% {\widetilde{g}}\\ &C}$
Definition 4 A $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$ring $A$ is finitely generated whenever there is some $n\in\mathbb{N}$ and some ideal $I\subseteq\mathcal{C}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$ such that $A\cong\dfrac{\mathcal{C}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n})}{I}$. The category of all finitely generated $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$rings is denoted by $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}{\rm\bf Rng}_{\rm fg}$.
Definition 2 Let $\mathfrak{A}=(A,\Phi)$ be a $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$structure. We say that $\mathfrak{A}$ (or, when there is no danger of confusion, $A$) is a $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$ring if the following is true: $\bullet$ Given any $n,k\in\mathbb{N}$ and any projection $p_{k}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$, we have: $\mathfrak{A}\models(\forall x_{1})\cdots(\forall x_{n})(p_{k}(x_{1},\cdots,x_{% n})=x_{k})$ $\bullet$ For every $f,g_{1},\cdots g_{n}\in\mathcal{C}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{m},\mathbb{R})$ with $m,n\in\mathbb{N}$, and every $h\in\mathcal{C}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n},\mathbb{R})$ such that $f=h\circ(g_{1},\cdots,g_{n})$, one has: $\mathfrak{A}\models(\forall x_{1})\cdots(\forall x_{m})(f(x_{1},\cdots,x_{m})=% h(g(x_{1},\cdots,x_{m}),\cdots,g_{n}(x_{1},\cdots,x_{m})))$
Definition 5 A $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$ring is finitely presented whenever there is some $n\in\mathbb{N}$ and some finitely generated ideal $I\subseteq\mathcal{C}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$ such that $A\cong\dfrac{\mathcal{C}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n})}{I}$. Whenever $A$ is a finitely presented $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$ring, there is some $n\in\mathbb{N}$ and some $f_{1},\cdots,f_{k}\in\mathcal{C}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$ such that: $A=\dfrac{\mathcal{C}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n})}{\langle f_{1},\cdots,f_{k}\rangle}$ The category of all finitely presented $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}-$rings is denoted by $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}{\rm\bf Rng}_{\rm fp}$
